WEBVTT

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:04.000
<v Teacher>Spanish dialects don't change very much.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.800
<v Teacher>Slang changes a lot, but Spanish is pretty standard.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:12.780
<v Teacher>It's not like Arabic for example, where you have such a different Arabic in Morocco to Egypt, for example.

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:17.740
<v Teacher>All of the different Spanishes are completely mutually intelligible.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:22.700
<v Teacher>But in slang, you get many different terms and words

00:00:22.700 --> 00:00:25.980
<v Teacher>and car is one of these words that have different versions.

00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:27.259
<v Teacher>Money is another one.

00:00:27.259 --> 00:00:30.779
<v Teacher>You might hear <b>dinero</b>, which is like the standard word;

00:00:30.779 --> 00:00:34.699
<v Teacher>you might hear <b>plata</b>, which actually means <i>silver</i>;

00:00:34.699 --> 00:00:39.040
<v Teacher><b>pasta</b> you might hear <b>pasta</b>, that's one they use that in Spain.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:43.360
<v Teacher>So we had a few words for car. Do you remember any of them?

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:46.260
<v Student><b>Máquina</b>, <b>auto</b>,

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:47.300
<v Student><b>caro</b>.

00:00:47.300 --> 00:00:49.379
<v Teacher><b>Carro</b>. Two <i>r</i>'s.

00:00:49.379 --> 00:00:51.940
<v Teacher>Let's stay with <b>carro</b>.

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:54.500
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>the car</i>?

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:56.160
<v Student><b>El carro</b>.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:59.360
<v Teacher><b>El carro</b>. And how would you say, <i>a car</i>?

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:00.720
<v Student><b>Un carro</b>.

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:06.560
<v Teacher><b>Un carro</b>. Good. So it's a masculine word, and we use <b>el</b> for <i>the</i>, and <b>un</b> for <i>a</i>.

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:10.480
<v Teacher>What if we say, <i>the cars</i>?

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:11.600
<v Student><b>Los carros</b>.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:16.240
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Los carros</b>. So the plural of <b>el</b> is <b>los</b>.

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:18.800
<v Teacher>It's a little bit different, <b>el</b> to <b>los</b>.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.280
<v Teacher>The word for <i>expensive</i> is <b>caro</b>.

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:26.640
<v Teacher>So it's like <b>carro</b>, but with one <i>r</i>. <b>Caro</b>.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:28.380
<v Student><b>Caro</b>.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:40.540
<v Teacher>So again it's a nice pair to feel the difference between having the single R and the double R, just as we saw in pero meaning but and pero meaning dog.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.720
<v Teacher>So how would you say the car is expensive?

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:47.520
<v Student>El carro is caro.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:48.240
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:51.040
<v Teacher><b>El carro es caro</b>. Good.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:02:02.259
<v Teacher>So <b>es</b> we said was <i>it is</i>, <i>she is</i>, <i>he is</i> or just <i>is</i>. Or <i>you are</i>, talking to <b>usted</b>. Talking formally.

00:02:02.259 --> 00:02:04.979
<v Teacher>So if you just wanted to say <i>it is expensive</i>:

00:02:05.840 --> 00:02:06.719
<v Student><b>Es caro</b>.

00:02:06.719 --> 00:02:10.080
<v Teacher>Good. And what if you were talking about a feminine thing?

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:11.440
<v Student><b>Es cara</b>.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:19.519
<v Teacher><b>Es cara</b>. And when I say feminine thing I really mean a feminine noun. If you're referring in your mind to a feminine noun, because

00:02:19.519 --> 00:02:26.720
<v Teacher>if you, in your country, call cars <b>máquinas</b>, then you're going to say <b>es cara</b>.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:30.420
<v Teacher>But if you call them <b>autos</b>, then you're going to say <b>es caro</b>.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:35.540
<v Teacher>So it refers to the word more than the object, to the noun, the gender of the noun.

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:48.760
<v Teacher>So <b>es</b> we have for <i>is</i>, and for <i>they are</i>, or <i>you guys are</i> - we know they always come together - we have <b>son</b>. <b>Son</b>. <i>S-o-n</i>.

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:49.960
<v Student><b>Son</b>.

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:55.480
<v Teacher><b>Son</b>. So if you want to say <i>the cars are expensive</i>, and we will use <b>carro</b> again.

00:02:55.480 --> 00:02:59.560
<v Teacher>So <i>the cars are expensive</i>:

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:05.000
<v Student><b>Los carros son caro</b>— <b>caros</b>.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.160
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Los carros son caros</b>. Good.

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:15.400
<v Teacher>What if you use a feminine word like <b>máquina</b>, how's it going to be? <i>The cars are expensive</i>:

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.600
<v Student><b>Las máquinas son caras</b>.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:20.840
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Las máquinas son caras</b>.

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:25.080
<v Teacher>And <i>the car is expensive</i>: Using again <b>máquina</b>.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:28.540
<v Student><b>La máquina es caro</b> - <b>cara</b>.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:31.420
<v Teacher>Good. <b>La máquina es cara</b>.

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:37.880
<v Teacher>The word <i>teacher</i> in Spanish is <b>profesor</b>. <b>Profesor</b>.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:38.920
<v Student><b>Profesor</b>.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:45.480
<v Teacher><b>Profesor</b>. So how would you say, <i>he is a professor</i>? And we don't need to say "a", we can just say <i>he is professor</i>.

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:47.900
<v Student><b>Es profesor</b>.

00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:50.299
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Es profesor</b>.

00:03:50.299 --> 00:03:53.340
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to say she is a professor?

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:55.500
<v Teacher>What do you think might happen?

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.360
<v Student>Es profesora?

00:03:58.599 --> 00:04:00.439
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Es profesora</b>.

00:04:00.439 --> 00:04:06.280
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to say, <i>they are teachers</i>, and you mean a group of females?

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.360
<v Student><b>Son profesoras</b>.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:12.720
<v Teacher><b>Son profesoras</b>. Good.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:16.280
<v Teacher>So, this is a noun, <b>profesor</b>.

00:04:16.280 --> 00:04:19.959
<v Teacher>It's a word you can put <i>the</i> or <i>a</i> in front of.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:27.040
<v Teacher>Now, we said that adjectives, they change for gender if they end in <i>-o</i>. If they don't, they don't.

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:34.800
<v Teacher>For example, <i>the global situation</i> was:

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:36.800
<v Student><b>La global situación</b>.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:40.340
<v Teacher>Where does that <b>global</b> go?

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:42.100
<v Student><b>La situación global</b>.

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:45.700
<v Teacher><b>La situación global</b>. So <b>situación</b> is feminine, but we're not saying "globala".

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:53.280
<v Teacher>Adjectives, these describing words that we can put <i>is</i> in front of, they only change if they end in <i>-o</i>.

00:04:53.280 --> 00:05:00.500
<v Teacher>But nouns, they can change to feminine like <b>profesor</b>/<b>profesora</b> to differentiate.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:05.640
<v Teacher>So this is why it's important to know what type of word we're dealing with.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:08.280
<v Teacher>We're doing this already, but we don't even realize it.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:14.920
<v Teacher>The moment we come in contact with a verb, we know exactly what to do. We know it's a verb, and we know how to manage it.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:19.259
<v Teacher>We don't start trying to make a verb masculine or feminine, for example.

00:05:19.259 --> 00:05:24.379
<v Teacher>So we are already making this differentiation, but we want to do it more consciously to get more control.

00:05:24.379 --> 00:05:28.220
<v Teacher>So this is a noun. <b>Doctor</b>, what do you think that means?

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:29.020
<v Student><b>Doctor</b>.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:33.340
<v Teacher>Good. Is it a noun, is it an adjective, is it a verb? What is it?

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:34.540
<v Student>Noun.

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:39.420
<v Teacher>Noun. So how do you think feminine, a female doctor, will be?

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:40.620
<v Student><b>Doctora</b>?

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:41.820
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Doctora</b>.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.020
<v Teacher>We just stick an A.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:43.340
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:45.740
<v Teacher>So how would you say he is a doctor?

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:47.980
<v Student>S Doctor.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:49.740
<v Teacher>Good. <i>She is a doctor</i>:

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:52.100
<v Student><b>Es doctora</b>.

00:05:52.100 --> 00:06:02.500
<v Teacher>Good. Now, if you want to get the plural of <b>profesor</b>, <b>profesor</b>, or <b>doctor</b>, <b>doctor</b>, or any other word

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:08.940
<v Teacher>in Spanish that ends in a consonant, you don't add <i>-s</i>; you add <i>-es</i>.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:12.780
<v Teacher>So how do you think it would sound, the plural of <b>profesor</b>?

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:14.940
<v Student><b>Profesores</b>.

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:17.020
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Profesores</b>.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:22.860
<v Teacher>So this is the plural for masculine or for mixed. The plural for feminine:

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:24.620
<v Student><b>Profesoras</b>.

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:27.260
<v Teacher>Good. So how would you say <i>they are professors</i>?

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:31.340
<v Teacher>And you mean a masculine or mixed group.

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:33.420
<v Student><b>Son profesores</b>.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:35.100
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son profesores</b>.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:37.740
<v Teacher>And if they were all female?

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.140
<v Student><b>Son profesoras</b>.

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:45.020
<v Teacher>Good. <i>They are doctors</i>: mixed or masculine:

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:46.780
<v Student><b>Son doctores</b>.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:48.700
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son doctores</b>.

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:50.940
<v Teacher>What if they were females?

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:52.780
<v Student><b>Son doctoras</b>.

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:55.340
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son doctoras</b>. Good.

00:06:55.340 --> 00:07:07.380
<v Teacher>Words ending <i>-ive</i> in English, <i>i-v-e</i>, tend to become <b>-ivo</b>, <i>i-v-o</i> for masculine singular.

00:07:07.380 --> 00:07:13.620
<v Teacher>This is the one we always start from though and build from, this masculine singular, or neuter let's say.

00:07:13.620 --> 00:07:16.860
<v Teacher>So for example <i>addictive</i> becomes <b>adictivo</b>.

00:07:16.860 --> 00:07:21.980
<v Teacher>Now when I say neuter, we don't really have a neuter in Spanish, we have masculine and feminine.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:24.300
<v Teacher>But the concept of neuter exists.

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:32.319
<v Teacher>For example, if I say <i>it's addictive</i>, and I'm referring to living in the mountains, <i>is addictive</i>;

00:07:32.319 --> 00:07:36.800
<v Teacher>eating healthily <i>is addictive</i> or something like this, then I use the masculine singular.

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:39.520
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>it's addictive</i>?

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:41.139
<v Student><b>Es adictivo</b>.

00:07:41.139 --> 00:07:42.900
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Es adictivo</b>.

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.020
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>he is positive</i>?

00:07:46.659 --> 00:07:47.699
<v Student><b>Es positivo</b>.

00:07:47.699 --> 00:08:03.040
<v Teacher>Good, and you pronounced an <i>s</i> where most English speakers will probably find themselves pronouncing a <i>z</i> there because in English we have <i>positive</i>, so that would probably transfer into Spanish to /pozitivo/ and we want to be careful not to do that.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:05.600
<v Teacher><b>Positivo</b> with an <i>s</i>. <b>Positivo</b>.

00:08:06.139 --> 00:08:08.460
<v Teacher><i>She is positive</i>:

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:09.660
<v Student><b>Es positiva</b>.

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:12.780
<v Teacher>Good. <i>They are positive</i>:

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.060
<v Student><b>Son positivos</b>.

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:16.860
<v Teacher>Good. <i>They are intuitive</i>:

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:19.500
<v Student><b>Son intuitivos</b>.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:21.420
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son intuitivos</b>.

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:23.900
<v Teacher>What if you meant women?

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:25.340
<v Student><b>Intuitivas</b>.

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:27.500
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son intuitivas</b>.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:30.460
<v Teacher><i>She is very attractive</i>:

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:35.260
<v Teacher>The word for <i>very</i> is <b>muy</b>, and it's spelled <i>m-u-y</i>.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:38.300
<v Teacher>The <i>y</i> you can imagine it like an <i>i</i>. <b>Muy</b>.

00:08:38.300 --> 00:08:39.180
<v Student><b>Muy</b>.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:41.900
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>she is very attractive</i>:

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:46.340
<v Student><b>Es muy atractivo</b>—

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:49.060
<v Student>oh, <b>atractiva</b>.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:52.100
<v Teacher><b>Atractiva</b>. <b>Es muy atractiva</b>.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:09:06.120
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Atractiva</b> is showing us that it refers to a female. So this would probably help us work out who we are talking about. But, maybe we would want to say, to clarify or to emphasize or to contrast.

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:12.060
<v Teacher>So how would you say that, using the word for <i>she</i>? <i>She is very attractive</i>:

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:17.580
<v Student>I always get confused on that, if it's <b>el</b> or if it's <b>la</b> or <b>ella</b>.

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:24.360
<v Teacher>So I want you to spend some time to think about it, and not guess. Think about which is which, make a decision.

00:09:24.959 --> 00:09:26.240
<v Student>Her is <b>la</b>.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:27.120
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:30.160
<v Student><b>Ella es muy atractiva</b>.

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.440
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Ella es muy atractiva</b>.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:36.399
<v Teacher>How would you say, <i>she is very creative</i>?

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:40.680
<v Student><b>Ella es muy creativa</b>.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:43.680
<v Teacher><i>But, she's aggressive</i>:

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:46.920
<v Student><b>Pero, es</b>— is it <b>agresiva</b>?

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:48.360
<v Student>I was thinking of the double <i>g</i>, does it stay?

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:56.440
<v Teacher>Well these random double letters that we don't need in English really, they just become single letters in Spanish.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:10:01.040
<v Teacher>So I think there's a double <i>s</i> there as well in English, well that would also become singular.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:07.120
<v Teacher>The only double letters that cross over are the <i>r</i>'s and the <i>n</i>'s. Like <b>connotación</b>.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:08.160
<v Student>Oh double <i>n</i>'s.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:09.920
<v Teacher>"Con-notación".

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:17.020
<v Teacher>If you get a double <i>f</i>, double <i>s</i>, double <i>g</i>, these random double letters you get in English; they don't cross over into Spanish.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:21.420
<v Teacher>How would you say, <i>they are aggressive</i>, talking about a masculine or mixed group?

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.180
<v Student><b>Son agresivos</b>.

00:10:24.180 --> 00:10:28.660
<v Teacher>Good. And what if you wanted to use the word for <i>they</i>?

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:31.540
<v Student><b>Ellos son agresivos</b>.

00:10:31.540 --> 00:10:35.220
<v Teacher>Good. How would you say, <i>he is negative</i>?

00:10:35.899 --> 00:10:37.180
<v Student><b>Es negativo</b>.

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:40.620
<v Teacher>Good, and if you use the word for <i>he</i>?

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:42.699
<v Student><b>Él es negativo</b>.

00:10:42.699 --> 00:10:45.980
<v Teacher>Good. <i>He is very negative</i>:

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:48.120
<v Student><b>Es muy negativo</b>.

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:53.160
<v Teacher>How would you say, <i>It's intensive</i>?

00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:55.380
<v Student><b>Es intensivo</b>.

00:10:55.380 --> 00:11:04.020
<v Teacher>Good. So we use the neuter there, we don't know what we're talking about. So we can just use the masculine singular, which is also like neuter.

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:06.100
<v Teacher><b>Es intensivo</b>.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:13.600
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>they are natives</i>?

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:15.120
<v Student><b>Son nativos</b>.

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:16.960
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Son nativos</b>.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:19.680
<v Teacher>And what if it was a female group?

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:21.580
<v Student><b>Son nativas</b>.

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:22.940
<v Teacher>Very good.

